\begin_layout Section
Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Measuring Business Closing Date
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Yelp data have a flag marking whether a business is Open or Closed,
 but this is not sufficient for our purposes as we need a date of closing
 as well.
 Our baseline measure will be that a business closed the day after its last
 review.
 However, this measure can be improved upon in a number of ways.
 Often when individuals find a business has shut down they give the business
 a poor review and write that the business has shut down in the text instead
 of filing the report on the Yelp.
 We will train a classifier to identify reviews of this type so we can improve
 our measurement of closing date for businesses marked as closed and so
 that we can identify other closed businesses.
 A further extension would be to develop a web crawler to check web archives
 so we could observe when a company's website goes down.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Measuring the importance of reviews
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The average number of starts a company receives in its ratings is an important
 measure 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Business Location
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We observe latitude an longitude for each business so we can create measures
 of the number of similar businesses nearby and the type of people who live
 (and possibly work) nearby.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Evaluation Criteria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Evaluation can take place at both a micro and macro level.
 Assuming our output is a probability of closing we could ask how close
 to we come predicting individual business closings.
 That is probably the question which is most interesting in machine learning.
 However, an economist would also be interested to know how well we predict
 the number of business closings in an area.
 For example, does our predicted number of closings for Phoenix line up
 with the number of closings in the next few months.
\end_layout

